This notebook is a part of a group assignment about investigating the data from the Brazilian e-commerce store Olist, however this part was only constructed by the author. This specific notebook will focus on customer review scores and comments as well as the the product categories that are more prone to customer dissatisfaction. The data used is generously provided by Olist and is downloaded from https://www.kaggle.com/olistbr/marketing-funnel-olist. An explantion of all the datafiles and their features can be found in the provided notebook Data-Description.ipynp. In the data company names are replaced with the names of Game of Thrones great houses.

Identifying critical product categories¶

In this section we would like to see how the ratings are distributed across the product categories to determine if some categories are more prone to bad reviews than others. Therefor the mean of the product reviews are first plotted for all categories

In [26]:
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(20, 8)})
size = df.groupby(['product_category_name_eng'])['review_score'].mean()
size = size.sort_values(ascending=False)
plt.bar(size.index,size)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

From this it can be seen that most categories are very close to the mean review score of 4. The last 5 categories are significant lower than that and therefor seem to be prone to more bad reviews. However, from a business perspective it does only make sense to look at a category if it acutally has a resonable amount of orders. As seen in the previous section the amount of orders in each category differ significant from each category. To have a better idea of which categories are interesting to look at both with regards to bad reviews while taking into account the total amount of orders, a plot showing the following is illustrated:

  • Numbers of orders within a category divided with the total amount of orders.
  • The total amount bad reviews for at category divided with the total amount of bad reviews for all categories.

With these two measures for each category the categories which have a large share of the bad reviews are easily spotted, however this ratio will be next to that categories share of all orders. If a category has a smaller amount of bad reviews than the amount of orders it means that this category is doing well, however if it has a larger share of bad reviews than it has of the orders then we might want to look into this category.

In [27]:
# Define a column specifying wheter an order is bad or good (1 = bad, 0 = good)
df['bad_reviews'] = (df['review_score'] < 3)*1

The amount of bad reviews, sales and total amount of reviews are found for each category.

reviews = df.groupby(['product_category_name_eng']).count()['review_score']

To be able to compare bad reviews, sales and total amount of reviews they have to be divided by the total amount. A new dataframe only containing these ratios is made and hereafter plotted.

In [29]:
# Create a datafram for the ratios
df_ratio = pd.DataFrame()
df_ratio['bad_reviews'] = bad_reviews/sum(bad_reviews)
df_ratio['reviews'] = reviews/sum(reviews)

# Fill the missing values as some categories do not have any bad reviews.
df_ratio = df_ratio.fillna(0)
In [30]:
## Plot the to ratios together for comparison.
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(20, 8)})
barWidth = 0.3
r1 = np.arange(len(df_ratio.index))
r2 = [x + barWidth for x in r1]



plt.bar(r1,df_ratio['bad_reviews'],width = barWidth,label='Bad reviews',color = 'tab:blue')
plt.bar(r2,df_ratio['reviews'],width = barWidth,label='Orders',color = 'tab:orange')
plt.legend()
plt.xticks([r + barWidth for r in range(len(df_ratio.index))], df_ratio.index, rotation=90)
plt.title("Ratios of the bad reviews and orders for all categories")
plt.show()

In the plot the blue bars are the ratio of the bad reviews for that category compared to the total amount of bad reviews. The orange bars are the ratio of the amount of orders compared to the total amount of orders. Below the key findings from the plot are stated:

  • From the plot it can be seen that a lot of the categories (such as 'air_conditioning', 'art' etc.) contributes with at small amount of the orders and also have very few reviews. These categories will not be looked into further as the gain from working with these for Olist would be limited.
  • There seems to be a tendency to that the ratio for the amount of orders is similar to the ratio for the amount of bad reviews. This intuitvely makes sense as the more orders a category has, the more bad reviews the category will probably get.
  • In total there are 5 categories which contributes with more than 6% of the orders each: bed_bath_table, bed_bath_table, furniture_decor, health_beauty and sports_leisure. All of these categories also have a large share of the bad reviews.
  • The category bed_bath_table has by far the biggest amount of bad reviews (almost 12%) but only has around 10% of the orders. A very similar pattern is seen for the category furniture_decor and computers_accessories.
  • The two categoris health_beauty and sports_leisures are both responsible for less of the bad reviews than the amount of ordres.
  • Of the 5 product categories which had the worst mean ratings only the category office_furniture has a noticable amount of orders. The category is also responsible for a noticable bigger amount of the bad reviews than the amont of orders it has. Therefor only this category of the 5 is looked into.

Of the categories discussed bed_bath_table, computers_accessories and furniture_decor are choosen as these have a much higher ratio of bad reviews than their ratio of orders. The categories are also some of the biggest categories with regards to amount of orders (all are within top 15) and improving on these can therefor potential give a lot of additional good reviews. office_furniture is also choosen as it had one of the lowest mean review scores and has a noticable amount of orders.

Below theses categories are plotted alone to be able to clearly see the distribution between them. Furthermore the amount of bad orders out of the total amount of orders within that category is added to the plot.

Single order customers vs. multiple order customers¶

A very obvious reason for Olist to want good reviews is to acquire new customers, if Olist have a bad rating many customers will look else where to make their purchase. Another reason for wanting good reviews could be with regards to returning customers. It is therefor interesting to understand if customers who made a single order and customers who made multiple orders give different ratings. To do this we use the customer_unique_id which is a unique id for each specific customers. Firstly let us recall how many customers we have and see how many bought from Olist multiple times.

Reviews over time¶

This section will investigate the reviews by looking at them over time. This can reveal any periods of the year with more bad reviews or any trends of the reviews. For the time of the review the feature order_purchase_timestamp is used which specifies the timestamp of the purchase. This is used as this date will show the current state of the company at that time. The feature review_creation_date could also have been used but as the reviews can be created long after the order is received this would not be directly related to anything happening in the company at that time.

To investigate this we will look at the mean review score, the ratio of the bad reviews and the different review score over time. The tool resample is used to accumulate observations over different time periods. This function can only resample over numbers so a column specifying if an observations is an order is needed.

In the plot the resampeling is kept at a monthly basis as if sampling over weeks too much detail was captured, and again, if sampeling over years too little detail could be captured. From the plot the following things are noted.

  • In the beginning (up until 2017-01) the company does not have many orders. This can be seen from the black line as a very small percentage of all the orders are in the first months. This is also the explanation to that purple and green line starts at ratio of 1.0, which indicates that in the first month all the reviews were bad. This is probably in the beginning phases of the company when they had very few orders.
  • Three of the 4 product categories do not have any reviews before the second month '2016-11'.
  • In the last month, 2018-10, there is very few observations and no observations for the choosen categories.
  • In 2017-12 the amount of bad reviews rises for all categories and at the same time the amount of orders rises. This might be because of the Christmas period where more orders are placed than normal (which means more bad reviews).
  • In the period of 2018-03 to 2018-04 all categories, but 'office_furniture', and the overall ratio reach their maximum ratio while the black line (Orders/total amonut of orders) stays unchanged. The increased amount of bad reviews are therefor not because of a sudden increase in orders.
  • The category 'office_furniture', which was the category which had the lowest mean review score of the categoreis, also generally has the worst ratio. In the beginning months this category has a lot of bad reivews, which could indicate some start up problems.

It can thus be concluded that for the period of time which is provided the ratio of bad ratings fluctuate alot but overall does not seem to be rising over time. There also seems to be time periods with more bad reviews than others. To further investigate the mean score for the different categories as well as the overall mean score is plotted.

From analysing the reviews over time it is thereby concluded that no general trend is seen over time. Two interesting time periods were however discovered, 1) Black Friday, which had by far the most amount of orders and reviews and 2) a period where there were more bad reviews than normal. Besides this it was found that the different product categories generally follow the same trend but that the category 'office_furniture' generally had the worst ratings of the 4 choosen categories.

Causes for bad reviews¶

This section will look into potential reason for the bad reviews, first by looking at late deliveries and after by analyzing the review comments.

Late deliveries¶

One reason for a bad review could be because of the order being late. To check this we need to check if order_estimated_delivery_date is larger than order_delivered_customer_date. As showed earlier there were some nan values for the feature order_delivered_customer_date which first must be removed.

In [55]:
df = df.dropna(subset = ['order_delivered_customer_date'])

In [75]:
import string
import re

## Definition for removing punctiations and making all letter lower case
def text_processing(text):
    ## Remove the punctiation
    text = "".join([c for c in text
                    if c not in string.punctuation])
    
    ## lower case
    text = "".join([c.lower() for c in text])
    
    ## Removing symbols
    text = re.sub(r'[^\w]', ' ', text)
    
    return text

def translation(dataframe_name):
    # Create empty column for the translated reviews
    dataframe_name['review_comment_message_eng'] = ''

    for i in range(0,len(dataframe_name)):
        temp = translator.translate(dataframe_name['review_comment_message'][i], src='pt',dest='en').text
        dataframe_name['review_comment_message_eng'][i] = temp
    
    return dataframe_name

## Import stop words
from sklearn.feature_extraction import stop_words

## Define a defeinition for removing stopwords
def remove_stopwords_eng(text):    
    # remove stopwords
    text = " ".join([w for w in text.split()
                    if w not in stop_words.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS])
    return text

Another defintion, remove_stopwords_por(text) is made for the exact same purpose but for the portuguese reviews. To remove the portuguese stop words stopwords from nltk.corpus is imported. from nltk.corpus import stopwords

def remove_stopwords_por(text):    
    # remove stopwords
    text = " ".join([w for w in text.split()
                    if w not in stopwords.words('portuguese')])
    return text

import wordcloud

def show_wordcloud(data, title):
    text = ' '.join(data.astype(str).tolist())
    stopwords = set(wordcloud.STOPWORDS)
    
    fig_wordcloud = wordcloud.WordCloud(stopwords=stopwords,
        max_font_size=100, max_words=100, background_color="white").generate(text)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,7), frameon=True)
    plt.imshow(fig_wordcloud, interpolation="bilinear")  
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.title(title, fontsize=20)
    plt.show()

TF-IDF - Term frequency - inverse document frequency

To get a better understanding of which words are most common in the reviews a TF-IDF analysis will be performed. The idea of the TF-IDF is that it penalises the frequent words and increase importance of rare words. To do this the TfidVectorizer from sklearn.feature_extraction.text is used.

In [134]:
# Import packages for analysing text
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer

To simplify the work with making a TF-IDF analysis a definition for analysing the english reviews tfidf_analyse is constructed and one for analysing the portuguese reviews tfidf_analyse_por. In the definition for analysing the portuguese reviews the Xth most common words are also traslated. Both definitions needs the name of the dataframe dataframe_name and the lower (ngram_range1) and upper (ngram_range2) bound of the range of n-values for different n-grams to be extracted. The difinition for the portuguese reviews further takes X which is the amount of n first words to be translated.

In [135]:
def tfidf_analyse(dataframe_name,ngram_range1,ngram_range2):
    # Set the tfidf vectorizer
    tfidf_vectorizer=TfidfVectorizer(use_idf=True, ngram_range 
                                     = (ngram_range1,ngram_range2))
    
    #Fit the TfidfVectorizer
    tfidf_vectorizer_vectors = tfidf_vectorizer.fit_transform(
                                dataframe_name['review_comment_message_eng'].values)
    
    # Compute the mean of the tfidf scores for all the reviews
    mean_tfidf = sum(tfidf_vectorizer_vectors[:]).T.todense()/dataframe_name.shape[0]
    
    # Place the scores in a pandas dataframe and sort by value
    temp = pd.DataFrame(mean_tfidf, index=tfidf_vectorizer.get_feature_names(),
                        columns=["tf-idf"])
    temp = temp.sort_values(by=["tf-idf"],ascending=False)
    
    # Return the dataframe
    return temp
In [136]:
def tfidf_analyse_por(dataframe_name, X,ngram_range1,ngram_range2):
    # Set the tfidf vectorizer
    tfidf_vectorizer=TfidfVectorizer(use_idf=True, ngram_range 
                                     = (ngram_range1,ngram_range2))
    
    #Fit the TfidfVectorizer
    tfidf_vectorizer_vectors = tfidf_vectorizer.fit_transform(
                               dataframe_name['review_comment_message'].values)

    
    # Compute the mean of the tfidf scores for all the reviews
    mean_tfidf = sum(tfidf_vectorizer_vectors[:]).T.todense()/dataframe_name.shape[0]
    
    # Place the scores in a pandas dataframe and sort by value
    temp = pd.DataFrame(mean_tfidf, index=tfidf_vectorizer.get_feature_names(),
                        columns=["tf-idf"])
    temp = temp.sort_values(by=["tf-idf"],ascending=False)
    
    # Translate the Xth first words
    temp['Translation'] = ' '
    
    for i in range(0,X):
        trans = translator.translate(temp.index[i], src='pt',dest='en').text
        temp['Translation'][i] = trans
    
    # Return the dataframe
    return temp

Topic modelling using LDA - Latent Dirichlet Allocation

To further understand and analyze specific problems topic modelling is also performed to discover 'topics' which are in the reviews. To this CountVectorizer is used to construct a bag-of-words and LatentDirichletAllocation from sklearn.

In [513]:
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation

Two defintions are therefor constructed. The defintion print_top_words is inspired by the definition with the same name from lecture 2 but is customized to return the translated result. This definition is used in another definition topic_model which takes data_frame, ngram_range1 and ngram_range2 which does the same as in the defintions for doing TF-IDF. The definition further take n_components which specifies the amount of topics and n_top which is the amount of top words to print.

In [729]:
def print_top_words(model, feature_names, n_top_words):
    norm = model.components_.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
    for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(model.components_):
        #Define empty vectors
        feat_names = []
        feat_names_trans = []
        print(80 * "-")
        print("Topic {}".format(topic_idx))
        for i in topic.argsort()[:-n_top_words - 1:-1]:
            #Append the names and their values
            feat_names.append(feature_names[i])
            feat_values.append(topic[i] / norm[topic_idx][0])
        #Translate
        for i in range(0,len(feat_names)):
            feat_names_trans.append(translator.translate(feat_names[i], src='pt',dest='en').text) 
        #Print
        for i in range(0,n_top_words):
            print(round(feat_values[i],4),
                  feat_names_trans[i])
In [702]:
def topic_model(data_frame, n_components, ngram_range1, ngram_range2, n_top):
    # Specify LDA
    LDA = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components = n_components, random_state = 42)
    # Bag of words
    count_vectorizer=CountVectorizer(ngram_range = (ngram_range1, ngram_range2))
    bow_counts =  count_vectorizer.fit_transform(data_frame['review_comment_message'].values)
    # Fit LDA
    lda_fitted = LDA.fit_transform(bow_counts)

    print("\nTopics in LDA model:")
    counts_feature_names = count_vectorizer.get_feature_names()
    n_top_words = n_top
    print_top_words(LDA, counts_feature_names, n_top_words)

When doing topic modelling all the reviews (both good and bad) are given to the model as the model then will figure out certain topics from this. First the topic modelling is applied for ngram_range = (1,2) and for 5 topics. This allows the model to choose both single words and two words. Stop words are also removed.

Conclusion¶

The overall conclusion from analysing the review comments is that the biggest problem is with regard to delivery as the orders are either late, gad not arrived or the wrong product was received. Other problems were also with regards to the quality of the product or missing parts.

For the different times it appeared that during Black Friday the main reason for the bad reviews were because of delivery problems as terms and topics relating to these were more frequent. During the period with a lot of review scores of 1, delivery is also one of the main reasons. During this periode the company 'Lannister' is further more mentioned which perhaps could be one of the reason to that the Olist for some months had a lower overall review rating, however this should be investigated further. When comparing to the baseline period and the results from analysing all reviews more terms and topics were about product quality, defect product or missing parts and less about delivery problems. This indicates that during periods like Black Friday, where demand is much higher than normal, extra focus should be used on optimizing the delivery.

When analyzing the review comment for the different product categories there were also problems with regard to late deliveries. More specifically customers were unhappy with the quality, and specifically bed covers are mentioned for the category bed_bath_table. The word photograph is also both present which could indicate that customers are unsatisfied with the photographs online compared to their own product. Cartridges (assumed printer cartridges) is complained about for the category computer_accessories, that products were defect, wrong product arrived and customers are asking for return and their money back. With regard to the category furniture_decor customers were unhappy about missing products, expensive freight. The company name Lannister also appeared, as it also did in the period with many reivew score of 1, which could indicate that this category might have problems with this specific company. Lastly for the category office_furniture the main problems appears to be with wrong or missing product or piece. More specifically there seems to be a lot of problems with the orders involving chairs.

Conclusion¶

Throughout the notebook many interesting topics have been touched upon. It has been established that returning customers generally do not give better reviews than customers who only place one order. Olist should therefor not put extra recources into returning customers, at least not with regards to review scores. 4 specific product categories have been identified: bed_bath_table, computer_accessories, furniture_decor and office_furniture, as these all had a significant amount of bad reviews and orders. It was further found that the during two periods the review scores deviated from the mean of 4: during Black Friday and during two months, 2018-03 to 2018-04.

The reason for bad reviews were overall found to be due to problems with late deliveries or product quality or defects. During the two periods it was found that delivery especially was a problem. Olist should therefor primally look into improving their delivery service and thereafter try solving the problems within the specified categories to improve their review scores.
